JO  - AMR
SP  - 416
EP  - 427
VL  - 25
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The authors contrast two hybrid dispute resolution procedures (arbitration-mediation and mediation-arbitration) that involve using mediation and arbitration in different sequences. The former's strengths stem from lowering disputant expectations and enhancing cooperative behaviors during the mediation phase. The latter procedure likely will be less costly and time consuming, enhance fairness judgments, and produce greater compliance to arbitrated decisions. The authors argue that the greatest benefit from arbitration-mediation is that it should encourage disputants to settle differences themselves.
AB  - The authors contrast two hybrid dispute resolution procedures (arbitration-mediation and mediation-arbitration) that involve using mediation and arbitration in different sequences. The former's strengths stem from lowering disputant expectations and enhancing cooperative behaviors during the mediation phase. The latter procedure likely will be less costly and time consuming, enhance fairness judgments, and produce greater compliance to arbitrated decisions. The authors argue that the greatest benefit from arbitration-mediation is that it should encourage disputants to settle differences themselves.
